        <h6>Week 3 (January 22nd)</h6>
        <h3>100 Ways of Seeing an Unequal World by Bob Suteliffe</h3>
        <p>Suteliffe, Bob. <em>100 Ways of Seeing an Unequal World.</em> Zed Books, 2001.</p>
        <p>I was in McFarlin when I stumbled accross this book while looking for another title, when I (admitedly) judged a book by its cover and thought this one might be interesting. Much to my delight it was a gold mine. Filled with graphs and charts depicting the inequality of the world it was right up my ally. Interestingly enough, this book was also first published in Spanish! Although it is a bit outdated by now, the graphical analysis of world inequalities is at the heart of my paper proposal and I am very excited to check out the list of references that will potentially lead me to more undated statistics. </p>
        <p>pg. 1</p>
        <blockquote>
            <p>Dos linajes solos hay en el mundo, como decía una abuela mía, que son el tener y el no tener.<br/></p>
        </blockquote>
        <p>This quote from <em>Don Quijote de la Mancha</em> reminds me a surprising amount to Voltaire’s <em>Candide</em> and Pangloss’s theory that “everything is best when it is worst.” Although they are saying two very different things (this quote roughly translates to: <em>There are two types of families in the world, those who have and those who don’t</em>). A quick google search tells me that <em>Candide</em> post-dates the publication of <em>Don Quijote de la Mancha</em> which would—if anything—suggest that Voltaire channeled a bit of Miguel de Cervantes here rather than the other way around.</p>
        <p>pg. 2</p>
        <blockquote>
            <p>I believe that it is imporant for socialists today to recapture the egalitarian spirit which was the heart of the historical utopian socialisms, including Marxism (3). Equality in this tradition is very far from homogeneity or conformity; it means the protection of freedom through equal civil and political rights and distribution according to need and not according to the ability to pay.</p>
        </blockquote>
        <p>The first thing that comes to mind when I read this is Ayn Rand&#39;s <em>Anthem</em>. I feel as if I am constantly baffled by how we can continue to be confronted with the same problems and conundrums hundreds of years later despite all of our &#39;advancements.&#39; Can we really be &#39;improving&#39; if we still behave just as bad as some of our &#39;barbaric&#39; ancestors?</p>
        <p>pg. 9</p>
        <blockquote>
            <p>That question is whether the multiple inequalities which we observe today, regardless of how they have changed in the recent or remote past, reveal unacceptable social injustices…My own reading of the evidence is that it would not give Sancho Panza&#39;s grandmother much cause to change the opinion she formed four hundred years ago.</p>
        </blockquote>
        <p>Wow. Talk about a heavy read. Although I have already finished part I of this book, I keep thinking back to this passage from the introduction. What I find particuarly striking here is his reference to the opening quote in this book—a line taken from <em>Don Quijote de la Manacha</em> that, at least for me, really drives home the idea that inequality in the world is nothing new. Something that makes solving some of the problems of today that much more impossible.</p>
        <hr />
        <h3>World War II in Numbers by Peter Doyle</h3>
        <p>Doyle, Peter. <em>World War II in Numbers: An Infographic Guide to the Conflict, its Conduct, and its Casualties</em>. A &amp; C Black, 2013.</p>
        <p>After randomly finding this book in the stacks of McFarlin, I skimmed through the pages looking for data visualization inspiration. Below are my comments and opinions on the methods used to present information.</p>
        <p>pg. 156</p>
        <p>A chart on this page shows the numbers of casualities by month representing a year as a circle. Since I don’t often think of a calendar year as being circular, it’s an interesting way to show the progression of time that seems to flow more naturally than a line of rectangles. </p>
        <p>As a side note: why aren’t there 360 days in a year? Why <em>are</em> there 365 degrees in a circle? Wouldn’t it be neat if they had the same amount? </p>
        <p>pg. 34</p>
        <p>Avoid having too much information on one page. It is really overwhelming when looking at it, and makes me just want to skip over it rather than take the time to try and understand what it is telling me. </p>
        <p>As a side note: I wonder if this is similar to why learning to write clearly is so important and why Dr. Peter’s is having us focus on telling stories. If we can’t convey our ideas then it becomes practically impossible to be understood both in the sense that people wont be willing to meet us half way and in the sense that on the off chance they do make it half way they are uninterested in going the rest of the way. </p>
        <p>pg.143</p>
        <p>There are quite a few graphs in this book that use little dots or mini people icons or some other definitive quantity to illustrate the total amount of something compared to those in other countries I really like this approach. After reading a bit about Edward R. Tufte earlier today and his idea of a ‘macro/micro’ data design in that from far away it just appears to be a bar graph, but close up you realize there is more than just lines to help you understand the information. </p>
