        <h3>Empathy and its Implications in Problem Solving</h3>
        <p>&quot;Empathetic Implications.&quot; <em>Cyberculture Since 1949</em>. University of Tulsa. 1 Feb 2018. Class Disconsciouslycussion. </p>
        <p>On Thurdsday we had a rather interesting discussion about how empathy and the degree to which people <em>care</em> about others impacts the way we solve problems. We began our discussion by considering how triage doctors are required to remove themselves from the situation in order to objectively analyze the situation and make practical decisions about which patient to care for first. It&#39;s an interesting question. In a profession where it seems is first and foremost about caring, how do you stop yourself from caring? </p>
        <p>The conversation then shifted to considering what happens when people become too removed from the situation and forget that they are dealing with people rather than problems that can be solved with pencil and paper. It was either Dana or Madi who brought up the problem that we seem to currently be facing where half the population seems to be diagnosed with ADHD based solely on a generalization of symptoms rather than considering the case as a whole for each individual. </p>
        <p>The dicussion also touched on social services and how its necessary to maintain a certain distance from your work in order to keep in mind what is realistic and best for everyone rather than just how you can &quot;fix&quot; the problem. This same problem is often found in unhealthy relationships where someone (conciously or otherwise) thinks that they can &quot;fix&quot; their partner, despite the fact that it is generally believed that a desire to &quot;fix&quot; someone should be an indication of two people being incompatible rather than caring for them. </p>
        <p>All in all, this got me thinking. If I am to be writing about inequality and looking at the data, is there a way that I should include more of the human element to things in order to ensure that I recognize that each number and statistic represents real-life beings rather than just arbitrary numbers? Is there a way I could include a first-hand narrative in my essay in order to highlight the privilege that we have? </p>
        <p>I wonder if a side-by-side chronology of someones day here, in the US, and in another country such as Venezuela or India would provide any additional meaning to the conceptualization of the numbers and metrics that I want to look at. </p>
        <p>I could also look at how people spend their time, which would be interesting, but then might also be too removed from the individual aspect of human inequality to fully appreciate the idea behind attempting to incorporate ways to be more empathetic in a data driven world. </p>
        <hr />
