        <h6>Week 6 (Feburary 12th)</h6>
        <h3>Atlas of Global Development by the World Bank</h3>
        <p>World Bank. <em>Atlas of Global Development: A Visual Guide to the World&#39;s Greatest Challenges.</em> Glasgow : Collins and the World Bank. World Bank. </p>
        <p>Goodness me, talk about heavy. Although this book is a bit outdated, I stumbled accross it while exploring the stacks of McFarlin and thought it was particuarly relevant. </p>
        <p>One thing that this book does that I really like is how it divided itself by various metrics without being too overwhelming. Each topic consists of 2-4 pages dicussing the topic with various statistics, charts and pictures for visualizations. Following each of these sections is a two-page spread of a world map depicting one of the metrics mentioned on the preceeding pages. Each section is color coded differently so that it is easy to tumb through the book and know where the topics being discussed change. </p>
        <p>One thing I didn&#39;t like about this book is its lack of foundational comprehension it presented. Sure, I can look at a graph and see one line is a lot taller than another, and interpret that as worse (or best, depending on the metrics) but it doesn&#39;t give me any sort of feel for what it is <em>really</em> trying to tell me, since it is only a line on a peice of paper. Hopefully, my final product can provide more of an insight to these numbers than this can.</p>
        <p>p. 43</p>
        <p>Some of the metrics that the World Bank used are really interesting. Such as on this page and the graph showing the mortality rate of children under the age of 5 relative to the amount of education that their mother has. It&#39;s quite astounding actually.</p>
        <p>p. 130</p>
        <p>At the very end of this book there is a breif section outlining why statistics are so imporant and thanking all statisticians for their service to aquiering such statistics. I&#39;ve never seen something like this before and find it rather interesting.</p>
