        <h3>What Does it Mean to Die? by Rachel Aviv</h3>
        <p>Aviv, Rachel. “What Does It Mean to Die?” <em>The New Yorker</em>, The New Yorker, 8 Feb. 2018, <a href='www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/02/05/what-does-it-mean-to-die.'>newyorker.com/magazine/2018/02/05/what-does-it-mean-to-die</a>. Accessed 15 Feb. 2018.</p>
        <blockquote>
            <p>“No one was listening to us, and I can’t prove it, but I really feel in my heart: if Jahi was a little white girl, I feel we would have gotten a little more help and attention.” </p>
        </blockquote>
        <p>This reminds me of a portion of Pease&#39;s book <em>Undoing Privilege</em> where he talks about how we often don&#39;t realize the extent of our privilege. If I get pulled over for speeding and let off with a warning, how much of my white-ness is contributing to getting off the hook for a ticket? Is this something that I should point out to the officer and subsequently request to be given a ticket?<br/></p>
        <blockquote>
            <p>African-Americans are twice as likely as whites to ask that their lives be prolonged as much as possible, even in cases of irreversible coma—a preference that likely stems from fears of neglect. A large body of research has shown that black patients are less likely to get appropriate medications and surgeries than white ones are, regardless of their insurance or education level, and more likely to receive undesirable medical interventions, like amputations.</p>
        </blockquote>
        <p>Although this isn&#39;t as applicable to world development as a whole, it does present an interesting perspective on some of the inequalities and privileges that occur within the United States.</p>
